# Day 1 – Git & GitHub Basics

## 🎯 Objective
Today I started my DevOps journey by learning the fundamentals of **Git** and **GitHub**.

---

# 📚 What I Learned

## 1. What is Git?

Git is a **Distributed Version Control System (VCS)** used to:

- Track changes in source code.
- Maintain project history.
- Restore previous versions.
- Collaborate with multiple developers.

Git is primarily used through the **Command Line Interface (CLI)**.

---

## 2. What is GitHub?

GitHub is a **cloud-based platform** that hosts Git repositories.

It helps developers:

- Store code remotely.
- Collaborate with teams.
- Review code through Pull Requests.
- Manage software projects.

---

## 3. Git vs GitHub

| Git | GitHub |
|------|---------|
| Version Control System | Cloud-based Platform |
| Installed on local machine | Hosted online |
| Tracks code changes | Hosts Git repositories |
| CLI-based | Web GUI |

---

## 4. Why Version Control?

### Without Version Control

- Deleted files may be permanently lost.
- Team members may overwrite each other's work.
- No history of changes.
- Difficult to revert mistakes.

### With Git

- Track every change.
- Restore previous versions.
- View commit history.
- Collaborate safely with teams.

---

# 💻 Git Commands Practiced

| Command | Purpose |
|---------|----------|
| `git init` | Initialize a new Git repository |
| `git status` | Show the status of tracked and untracked files |
| `git add <filename>` | Stage a specific file |
| `git add .` | Stage all modified files |
| `git commit -m "message"` | Save a snapshot of staged changes |
| `git restore <filename>` | Restore changes made to a tracked file |
| `git rm --cached <filename>` | Remove a file from Git tracking while keeping it locally |
| `git remote add origin <repository-url>` | Connect the local repository to GitHub |
| `git push origin main` | Push commits to the remote repository |

---

# 🔐 Authentication

Today I learned about **Personal Access Tokens (PATs).**

GitHub no longer supports password authentication over HTTPS. Instead, developers use PATs for secure authentication.

Example:

```bash
git remote set-url origin https://<TOKEN>@github.com/username/repository.git
```

> **Note:** Although embedding a PAT in the URL works, it is more secure to use **Git Credential Manager** or **SSH keys** so your token is not stored in the remote URL.

---

# ✅ Key Takeaways

- Git and GitHub are different tools that work together.
- Version control helps developers track and manage code changes.
- GitHub enables remote code hosting and collaboration.
- Commits create checkpoints in project history.
- Personal Access Tokens (PATs) provide secure authentication.

